## Enhancement 4: Smarter Text Matching

**Problem**: Current text comparison is **binary** (substring match or zero). Many semantically close values get 0:

| Your PDF | Competitor | Current Score | Better Score |
|---|---|---|---|
| `"QFN-8"` | `"QFN-10"` | 0% | ~80% (same package family) |
| `"I2C, SPI"` | `"SPI, I2C"` | 100% (lucky substring) | 100% (set overlap) |
| `"Fixed"` | `"Fixed, Adjustable"` | 100% (substring) | 100% ✓ |
| `"LGA-12"` | `"VLGA-12"` | 0% | ~90% (very similar) |

**Proposed fix** — set-based matching for multi-value features:
```python
def text_similarity_score(user_val: str, comp_val: str, weight: int) -> float:
    """Score text features using set overlap instead of substring matching."""
    # Split on common delimiters: comma, slash, ampersand, semicolon
    user_tokens = set(
        t.strip().lower() for t in re.split(r'[,/&;]', str(user_val)) if t.strip()
    )
    comp_tokens = set(
        t.strip().lower() for t in re.split(r'[,/&;]', str(comp_val)) if t.strip()
    )

    if not user_tokens:
        return 0

    # Check exact set overlap first
    overlap = len(user_tokens & comp_tokens)
    if overlap > 0:
        return weight * (overlap / len(user_tokens))

    # Fallback: substring check on the full strings (current behavior)
    u_str = str(user_val).lower()
    c_str = str(comp_val).lower()
    if u_str in c_str or c_str in u_str:
        return weight

    return 0
```

**Impact**: More accurate scoring for package types, interface protocols, and multi-option features. Prevents lucky/unlucky substring matches from dominating scores.

